messages.text: Several weeks later, Taylor, Blake, and Blake‚Äôs date, Star, attend a gallery opening hosting multiple artists.
Servers hustle by with silver trays topped with champagne.
Blake lifts two flutes and passes them to Taylor and Star before taking one for himself.
He motions to a painting with his glass.
What the hell am I looking at now?
A woman.
Not a man?
No. It‚Äôs a woman‚Ä¶maybe.
Are you sure? She looks‚Ä¶off.
That‚Äôs because she‚Äôs a horse.
That‚Äôs a horse?
An ugly horse.
You‚Äôre being loud.
I‚Äôm always loud.
Damn. This piece sucks.
Keep it down.
Like someone or something threw up on happiness.
People are watching.
And all over the fugly horse.
Is it too much to ask for you to be quiet?
Yup. Why does that shock you?
Damn it, woman.
You know what your problem is?
I asked you here?
You‚Äôre too uptight.
I am not.
That‚Äôs what people who are too uptight always say.
Don‚Äôt worry. We‚Äôll work on it.
There‚Äôs nothing to work on.
Trust me, pretty boy, there is.
Star taps his back and chugs her champagne, dropping the flute on a passing tray as she heads toward the restrooms.
You like her. Don‚Äôt you?
Star? Are you kidding?
Did you not see our interaction?
I did. I almost told you to get a room.
You‚Ä¶I can‚Äôt believe‚Ä¶I‚Äôm not attracted to her!
The why did you ask her here? And why can‚Äôt you seem to rip your eyes off her?
I was trying to be nice.
By ogling her?
She‚Äôs a friend of Jonathan‚Äôs!
Hmm‚Ä¶She‚Äôs why you‚Äôve been so busy lately.
You act like we‚Äôre dating.
What do you call this?
Me being nice.
And why are you yelling?
I‚Äôm not yelling!
Taylor laughs as Blake struggles to compose himself
Do the servers a favor and roll your tongue back in your mouth before someone trips on it.
Sorry.
Sorry about what? Looking at another woman?
Yeah. It‚Äôs not right. Not around you.
If we‚Äôre just friends it should be.
I don‚Äôt know about that.
What‚Äôs stopping you from asking Star out on a real date? One without me present?
She‚Äôs not my type.
Why? She‚Äôs beautiful.
Tay, she has purple hair.
And?
And don‚Äôt get me started on the damn piercing.
The one on her lip? The one it seems you want to nibble?
Tay, I‚Äôm not having this conversation with you.
Why?
Maybe I want to hang on to the last shred of decency I have left.
You‚Äôre not a bad guy, Blake. We‚Äôve all made bad decisions.
Stop punishing yourself. I want you to be happy.
I want that for you, too.
I know. I‚Äôm just not sure it‚Äôs going to happen‚Ä¶
Dudes! There‚Äôs a rendition of first Thanksgiving except with cats. Cats! Seriously, you have to see it.
Why would I want to see that?
Because you could use a good laugh, and damn it all, I like cats.
You‚Äôre being loud.
And you‚Äôre being uptight. Again.
Besides, one man‚Äôs art is another‚Ä¶never mind. I just like cats!
Stop pulling me.
Stop being a buzz kill.
Don‚Äôt you have manners to find?
Don‚Äôt you have a mood to kill?
Do you have to be so loud?
Do you have to be so uptight?
You‚Äôre lucky I‚Äôm a gentleman.
And you‚Äôre lucky you‚Äôre pretty.
Stop calling me that!
It makes up for your lack of personality. But just a little bit.
I have personality!
Yeah. It shows. Come on, Taylor.
You go ahead. I‚Äôm going to look around.
Taylor smiles as she watches Star strut away with Blake who once more is struggling to compose himself.
It‚Äôs easy to leave Blake alone with a beautiful woman.
Too easy.
Taylor was never the jealous type.
She‚Äôd been hurt by the betrayal, yes.
But she was never jealous.
The only time Taylor felt threatened by a woman was when she‚Äôd see one with‚Ä¶
Jonathan.
Taylor‚Äôs heart sinks when stops in front another painting and she immediately thinks of him.
God, I miss you.
I miss your smile.
Her eyes pass along the abstract painting created in hues of blues and grays.
Sadness grips her as she takes in each stroke and whisper of color.
She gasps and brings her hand up to cover her mouth.
The emotions the painting stirs are so intense, they freeze her in place.
Taylor reaches out, her fingers lingering mere centimeters away from the canvas.
She pulls her hand away, and her gaze searches for the name of the artist.
The painting isn‚Äôt signed, and the brass plate fixed to the frame is blank.
Do you like it?
Taylor trembles, from shock of finding him here and maybe something else.
She turns slowly to see Jonathan‚Äôs face.
It‚Äôs yours, isn‚Äôt it?
How did you know?
I‚Äôd know you anywhere.
Jonathan bows his head.
What do you think of it?
It‚Äôs beautiful‚Ä¶
Heartbreaking.
Your best work.
You think so?
I really do.
Your soul is in every stroke.
You had to go and say that, didn‚Äôt you?
Am I wrong?
No.
Patrons shuffle around them, admiring the piece as the silence stretches between Jonathan and Taylor.
Look, I know you told me to stay away.
But technically you came to me.
What are you talking about?
There‚Äôre various pieces by other artists on display, but I‚Äôm the featured artist.
Didn‚Äôt Blake tell you?
No, he just ‚Äî he said I needed to get out.
That he had extra tickets to an art exhibit in the city.
Who do you think gave him those tickets?
Taylor tries to take a sip of her champagne.
Thinking better of it, she hands her glass to a passing server.
Did you tell Blake to bring me?
No. I couldn‚Äôt do that to him.
Did you want him to bring me?
A few minutes pass.
Please tell me.
Did you want me to come?
Yes.
But I never dreamed that you would.
What do you call it?
What?
The painting. What‚Äôs it called?
Lost.
Tears well in Jonathan‚Äôs eyes.
I painted it the day you walked away from me.
Taylor doesn‚Äôt think about the consequences.
She closes the distance between them, her arms circling Jonathan‚Äôs waist.
Jonathan gathers Taylor close.
I don‚Äôt want to let you go.
Jesus, I NEVER want to let you go again‚Ä¶
